ts":[]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","meanings":["Greek: the Lord gave graciously; whom Jehovah gave; whom Jehovah bestowed."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":27,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705197,"age":100,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When John Ingleby was born in 1355, in High Harrogate, Yorkshire, England, his father, Sir Thomas Ingleby Knight, was 38 and his mother, Margaret Mowbrey, was 26. He had at least 1 son with Ellen Rocliffe. His occupation is listed as lord of the manor, part founder of mount grace abbey (monastery) in Ripley, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom. He died in England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1355–":"1355–Surnud","1355–Male":"1355–Surnud","1350–1400":"1350–1400","1378–1420":"1378–1420","1318–Male":"1318–Surnud","1330–Female":"1330–Surnud","1455":"1455","1378":"1378","1400":"1400","1355":"1355","1420":"1420","about 1378":"umbes 1378","1330":"1330","1350":"1350","1382":"1382","1318":"1318","High Harrogate, Yorkshire, England":"High Harrogate, Yorkshire, England","Ripley, Yorkshire, England":"Ripley, Yorkshire, England","England":"I